liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Monash University lecturer and analyst on Israel and Middle Eastern Affairs Dr Ran Porat has spoken with ABC News, about how the unity government in Israel will work. "The practicalities of this government will be mostly around the cabinet and the additional minister that will join the government," Dr Porat has told ABC News. "There is going to be five new ministers with no official titles and others will stand at the side as onlookers." "The thing is the government will be stuck with a lot of veteran politicians and veterinary IDF, Israeli army commanders, including two former chief of staff themselves," Dr Porat says. "The idea is to have people with experience in operational aspects of war with consideration or considering the implications of specific rules and also discussing what is on everybody's mind the day after, what will happen, what is the exit strategy of this war in response to Hamas's horrendous attack on Israeli." He says it is a "positive step in the eyes of the Israeli public." Dr Porat says despite the unity government forming, the criticisms of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and his government will not go away. "It is put on ice but it does not go away." "[Mr] Netanyahu did make it clear he will not put anything controversial now which is expected, but people in Israel have not forgotten [the judicial overhaul]." " Many on the camp that objected to the judicial overhaul see [Mr] Netanyahu possibly with some truth behind him that he is responsible for this global failure. " " The divisions in Israel is understood [to be] around the Middle East as a sign of weakness. " It is something that the enemies of Israel saw fit as a sort of opportunity to attack Israel because they saw Israel as weak." Dr Porat says all the divisions have been put aside and says the Israeli public is completely behind the war efforts.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Dr Ran Porat explains how Israel's unity government will work

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: By political reporter Jake Evans Foreign Affairs Minister Penny Wong has confirmed a third repatriation flight for citizens in Israel is being arranged. The flight will leave early next week with further details to be released by the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade within the next 24 hours. Senator Wong says the department is coordinating the flight, and anyone seeking to leave should register their interest through Smart Traveller. She said the government was considering whether further flights were needed. "I did last night agree to a third flight," she said. "My anticipation is that demand will require at least a further flight. We will look at whether any further assisted departures are required."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Penny Wong confirms third repatriation flight for Australians in Israel

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Joe Biden has been meeting with Jewish community leaders in Washington, telling them the US was warning Iran to "be careful". "This attack was a campaign of pure cruelty – not just hate, but cruelty – against the Jewish people," he told the gathering at the White House. "I would argue it's the deadliest day for Jews since the Holocaust." The US president said he'd spoken again to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu today, and he'd promised him more military aid. America is also bolstering its military presence in the broader region to deter other enemies of Israel from trying to widen the war. "We moved the US carrier fleet to the eastern Mediterranean and we are sending more fighter jets to that region and made it clear to the Iranians — be careful," he said. Earlier, White House national security spokesman John Kirby said there was no evidence linking Iran directly to Saturday's attack. But he said security agencies would "continue to look at the intelligence stream and see if it leads us to different conclusions".
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Biden says Hamas attack was a campaign of 'pure cruelty' against Jewish people, warns Iran to 'be careful'

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Jessica Warriner SA Premier Peter Malinauskas and opposition leader David Speirs have both spoken on ABC Radio Adelaide this morning ahead of Saturday's referendum. Talkback callers asked how a potential federal Voice would interact with SA's own Voice to Parliament. Mr Malinauskas, in the Yes camp, said the two are "completely separate propositions". "If there's a Yes outcome on the weekend, the state-based Voice and the federally-based Voice will be unique," he said. "That is in many respects no different to countless other organisations that the parliament and government have set up to provide on any number of decisions." Mr Speirs, a No campaigner, was also asked by callers if he were to win the next election, would the Liberals change the state Voice. "I've been very clear publicly that we would watch the state-based Voice as it unfolded and would be open to amending it or changing the way it worked, if it wasn't working effectively," he said. "We'll have to see the outcome in South Australia on Saturday evening or Sunday when those results become apparent as to whether a No vote in South Australia can be read as a lack of support for the premier's legislated state-based voice."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: South Australian premier and opposition leader debate Voice

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Jake Evans Independent senator Lidia Thorpe, who has become a figurehead for progressive opponents of the Voice to Parliament, says the body should be enshrined in law even if the referendum fails. Senator Thorpe told ABC Radio National Breakfast that the prime minister's comments on the weekend he would abandon the Voice proposal if Australians vote it down was "weak". "It's a weak response, it's like, 'I throw my bat and run away, I don't want to play no more,' attitude," she said. The independent senator said she was opposed to the Voice being used as "window dressing" for Indigenous recognition in the constitution, which she views as insufficient to address Australia's colonial history. But Senator Thorpe said there should still be a Voice to Parliament, saying she would support legislation if it was not tied to the constitution.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Lidia Thorpe says Voice should still be legislated if referendum fails

featuredLink.title: Lidia Thorpe, a No campaigner against the Voice, says Voice should be legislated if referendum fails

children.content: Lidia Thorpe says the nation needs a Voice to Parliament, though she is campaigning against the referendum proposal.

Reporting by Jake Evans
Independent senator
Lidia Thorpe
, who has become a figurehead for progressive opponents of the Voice to Parliament, says the body should be enshrined in law even if the referendum fails.
Senator Thorpe told ABC Radio National Breakfast that the prime minister's comments on the weekend he would abandon the Voice proposal if Australians vote it down was "weak".
"It's a weak response, it's like, 'I throw my bat and run away, I don't want to play no more,' attitude," she said.

The independent senator said she was opposed to the Voice being used as "window dressing" for Indigenous recognition in the constitution, which she views as insufficient to address Australia's colonial history.
But Senator Thorpe said there should still be a Voice to Parliament, saying she would support legislation if it was not tied to the constitution.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Lucas Forbes Sebastian and Ella McCorry are helping their fellow students get the right information ahead of the Voice referendum poll, amid concern about inaccurate social media posts. The eighteen-year-old Wiradjuri twins have been frustrated by misinformation about the Voice to Parliament referendum on TikTok and Facebook. They're part of their school's student representative council, which has been running Q & A sessions with younger students about the Voice. The council has also written to the parents of year 12 students, urging them to seek reliable information. Read more about Sebastian and Ella's work below.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Gold is that trusted safe haven in times of woe. With the conflict in Israel, Ukraine still fighting its war, a dip in US Treasury yields and broad-based global economic downturn, the spot gold price is nudging $US1,900 an ounce at the moment. We're seeing gold stocks track higher today - the sub sector is up more than 2 per cent this morning. Shares of Newcrest Mining have risen as much as 2.4% to $25.88, their highest since September 27, after shareholders of suitor Newmont vote in favour of its $16.80 billon buyout Shares of Northern Star Resources have climbed as much as 2.3% to $11.52, their highest since September 19. Evolution Mining's stock is also up 1.55% to $3.61.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Gold stocks are sizzling
